{
  "title": "Impact of Histopathological Feature Encoding on Machine Learning Prediction of Sperm Retrieval in Micro-TESE for Non-Obstructive Azoospermia: A Comparative Analysis of 16 Encoding Strategies",
  "authors": "Hossein Jamalirad, Marjan Sabbaghian, Hassan Vakili Arki",
  "abstract": "Background: Non-obstructive azoospermia (NOA) affects approximately 10% of infertile men and represents the most severe form of male infertility. Microsurgical testicular sperm extraction (micro-TESE) is the gold standard for sperm retrieval, yet success rates vary widely (40-60%). While machine learning (ML) approaches have shown promise in predicting micro-TESE outcomes, the impact of histopathological feature encoding strategies on model performance has not been systematically investigated. Methods: We performed a retrospective analysis of 2,413 NOA patients who underwent micro-TESE at Royan Institute, Tehran, Iran. Sixteen encoding strategies for bilateral testicular biopsy histopathological features were designed and evaluated across five ML classifiers using 5×5 nested cross-validation with 50-iteration randomized hyperparameter search per fold. Results: The ordinal_detailed_plus_raw encoding strategy, which combines per-testis ordinal severity scores with 16 raw histopathological percentage features, achieved optimal performance. CatBoost attained the highest AUC of 0.8306 (bootstrap 95% CI: 0.813–0.846), with sensitivity of 0.678, specificity of 0.822, and F1 of 0.658. SHAP analysis revealed that 17 of 25 top features were pathology-derived, with right testicular severe hypospermatogenesis percentage being the single most influential predictor. Conclusion: Systematic encoding of histopathological features substantially impacts ML-based prediction of sperm retrieval in micro-TESE. The proposed ordinal encoding with raw feature preservation achieves state-of-the-art prediction performance and provides clinically interpretable feature attributions.",
  "key_results_summary": "The ordinal_detailed_plus_raw encoding strategy achieved the best CatBoost AUC of 0.8306 (95% CI: 0.813–0.846), significantly outperforming other encoding approaches. SHAP analysis showed 17 of 25 top features were pathology-derived, with right testicular severe hypospermatogenesis being most influential. Clinical-only baseline achieved near-chance AUC (0.5642), confirming the critical importance of histopathological features.",
